  "body": "Let's say we have a class like this:\n\n```\nexport default class BasePlayer extends React.Component {\n      myMethod(){ }\n}\n```\n\nThen, if I use this BasePlayer inside another component and I name it with \"ref=basePlayer\", like this:\n\n```\nclass SomeComponent extends React.Component {\n    ...\n   render(){\n        return <div><BasePlayer ref=\"basePlayer\" /></div>\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThe problem is that, from the class SomeComponent I can't call \"this.refs.basePlayer.myMethod()\", because the methods are not binded to the basePlayer instance.\n\nTo fixed it what I did was, to manually bind/expose my methods from the BasePlayer constructor like this:\n\n```\nconstructor(props){\n    super(props);\n\n    /*public methods*/ \n    this.myMethod= this.myMethod;\n}\n```\n\nBut it should be automatic... Is there a better way to achieve this?\n",
